The old kiosk mode code used localstorage and would show/hide elements if the kiosk mode is enabled. Can you update this to work with the new cookie-based solution?
Certainly! We can update the code to work with the new cookie-based solution while maintaining the functionality of showing/hiding elements based on the kiosk mode state. Here's how we can modify the TypeScript and HTML to achieve this:

1. Update the TypeScript file (`kiosk_mode.ts`):

```typescript
import onLoad from '../../../static/js/onLoad';
import querySelectorOrThrow from '../../../static/js/querySelectorOrThrow';

const isKioskMode = () => document.cookie.includes('kiosk_mode=on');

const hideKioskElements = () => {
  const active = isKioskMode();
  document.body
    .querySelectorAll('.hide-for-kiosk-mode')
    .forEach((e) => e.classList.toggle('!_hidden', active));
};

const initKioskMode = () => {
  const kioskToggle = querySelectorOrThrow<HTMLInputElement>(
    document,
    '#kiosk-mode'
  );

  kioskToggle.checked = isKioskMode();

  hideKioskElements();

  kioskToggle.addEventListener('change', () => {
    // The actual toggle is handled by HTMX, so we just need to update the UI
    hideKioskElements();
  });

  document.body.addEventListener('htmx:afterOnLoad', () => {
    hideKioskElements();
  });
};

onLoad(() => {
  initKioskMode();
});
```

2. Update the HTML file (`kiosk_mode_toggle.html`):

```html
{% from "rainbow/components/tooltip/macros.html" import TooltipItem %}

<div id="kiosk-toggle" class="_flex _items-center _tooltip_wrapper">
    <input type="checkbox"
           class="_toggle-field"
           {% if kiosk_mode == 'on' %}checked{% endif %}
           hx-get="{{ url('interests:toggle-kiosk-mode') }}"
           hx-target="#kiosk-toggle"
           hx-swap="outerHTML"
           hx-trigger="change"
           id="kiosk-mode"
           name="kiosk-mode">
    <label for="kiosk-mode">
        <span class="_sr-only">{{ _('Kiosk Mode') }}</span>
    </label>
    {% call TooltipItem(extra_classes='_bg-lilac-100 _min-w-max _mt-1') %}
    <div class="_normal-case _text-left _text-white _body-xs">{{ _('Kiosk Mode') }}</div>
    {% endcall %}
</div>
```

Key changes and explanations:

1. In the TypeScript file:
   - We've updated `isKioskMode()` to check the cookie instead of localStorage.
   - We've removed `setKioskMode()` as the cookie is now set by the server.
   - The `hideKioskElements()` function remains largely the same, toggling the visibility of elements with the 'hide-for-kiosk-mode' class.
   - In `initKioskMode()`, we still set the initial state of the checkbox and hide elements, but we don't need to manually update the cookie on change.
   - We've kept the 'htmx:afterOnLoad' event listener to ensure elements are hidden/shown correctly after HTMX updates.

2. In the HTML file:
   - We've added `hx-trigger="change"` to ensure the HTMX request is sent when the checkbox state changes.

This setup maintains the functionality of showing/hiding elements based on kiosk mode while using the new cookie-based solution. The server handles the state persistence, and the client-side script takes care of updating the UI accordingly.

Remember to ensure that your server-side code is setting the 'kiosk_mode' cookie correctly when toggling the mode.
I want to encapsulate this string in a jinja variable. `hide-for-kiosk-mode {% if kiosk_mode == 'on' %}!_hidden{% endif %}` so that we can easily add it to class name attributes.
Certainly! You can create a Jinja macro to encapsulate this logic and make it easy to reuse throughout your templates. Here's how you can do it:

1. First, create a new Jinja macro file, let's call it `kiosk_mode_macros.html`:

```html
{% macro kiosk_mode_class() %}
hide-for-kiosk-mode{% if kiosk_mode == 'on' %} !_hidden{% endif %}
{% endmacro %}
```

2. Now, in any template where you want to use this class, you can import and use the macro like this:

```html
{% from "path/to/kiosk_mode_macros.html" import kiosk_mode_class %}

<div class="your-regular-classes {{ kiosk_mode_class() }}">
    <!-- Your content here -->
</div>
```

3. If you want to make this macro globally available in all your templates, you can add it to your Jinja environment setup in your Django settings or wherever you configure your Jinja environment. For example:

```python
def environment(**options):
    env = Environment(**options)
    env.globals.update({
        'kiosk_mode_class': lambda: 'hide-for-kiosk-mode' + (' !_hidden' if options.get('kiosk_mode') == 'on' else '')
    })
    return env
```

Then you could use it in any template without importing:

```html
<div class="your-regular-classes {{ kiosk_mode_class() }}">
    <!-- Your content here -->
</div>
```

4. Alternatively, if you're using Django's template system instead of Jinja, you can create a custom template tag. Create a file named `templatetags/kiosk_mode_tags.py` in your app:

```python
from django import template

register = template.Library()

@register.simple_tag(takes_context=True)
def kiosk_mode_class(context):
    kiosk_mode = context.get('kiosk_mode')
    return f"hide-for-kiosk-mode{'!_hidden' if kiosk_mode == 'on' else ''}"
```

Then use it in your templates like this:

```html
{% load kiosk_mode_tags %}

<div class="your-regular-classes {% kiosk_mode_class %}">
    <!-- Your content here -->
</div>
```

These approaches allow you to encapsulate the kiosk mode class logic and easily apply it to any element that needs to be hidden in kiosk mode. Choose the method that best fits your project structure and templating system.


how do I do a full page reload in js?
To perform a full page reload in JavaScript, you have a few options:

1. Using `location.reload()`:
   This is the most straightforward method:

   ```javascript
   window.location.reload();
   ```

   Or, to force a reload from the server (bypassing the cache):

   ```javascript
   window.location.reload(true);
   ```

2. Reassigning the `location`:
   You can reassign the current URL to `location`:

   ```javascript
   window.location = window.location.href;
   ```

   Or:

   ```javascript
   window.location.assign(window.location.href);
   ```

3. Using the `history` API:
   This method navigates to the current page:

   ```javascript
   history.go(0);
   ```

4. Replacing the entire URL:
   This replaces the current entry in the session history:

   ```javascript
   window.location.replace(window.location.href);
   ```

Each of these methods will cause the browser to reload the current page. The `location.reload(true)` method is often preferred when you want to ensure the browser fetches the latest version of the page from the server, bypassing any cached version.

Remember that a full page reload will cause the entire page to be reloaded, which might not always be necessary or desirable for performance reasons. In many modern web applications, developers often prefer to update only parts of the page using AJAX or other techniques to provide a smoother user experience.
fix this query selector for me `  const state = document.querySelector('#kiosk-toggle > input.type[checkbox]')`

Certainly! The selector you provided has a few issues. Here's the corrected version:

```javascript
const state = document.querySelector('#kiosk-toggle > input[type="checkbox"]');
```

Here's what was changed:

1. The attribute selector syntax was incorrect. It should be `[type="checkbox"]` instead of `.type[checkbox]`.
2. The value "checkbox" should be in quotes within the attribute selector.

This selector will:
1. Find an element with the ID "kiosk-toggle"
2. Look for an immediate child (`>`) that is an `input` element
3. The input element should have a `type` attribute with the value "checkbox"

If you want to make it even more specific, you could add the class selector if your checkbox has a specific class:

```javascript
const state = document.querySelector('#kiosk-toggle > input[type="checkbox"]._toggle-field');
```

This assumes the checkbox has a class `_toggle-field` as shown in your HTML snippet.

Remember, `querySelector` returns the first matching element. If you expect multiple checkboxes and want to select all of them, you should use `querySelectorAll` instead.
best way of checking if an input is checked?
The best and most straightforward way to check if an input checkbox is checked in JavaScript is to use the `checked` property. Here are a few ways to do this:

1. Direct property access:
   ```javascript
   const checkbox = document.querySelector('#myCheckbox');
   if (checkbox.checked) {
       // Checkbox is checked
   } else {
       // Checkbox is not checked
   }
   ```

2. Using a conditional (ternary) operator:
   ```javascript
   const isChecked = checkbox.checked ? true : false;
   ```

3. Using double negation for a boolean result:
   ```javascript
   const isChecked = !!checkbox.checked;
   ```

4. If you're dealing with a form and know the name of the checkbox:
   ```javascript
   const isChecked = document.forms['myForm']['checkboxName'].checked;
   ```

5. If you're using jQuery (though it's less common nowadays):
   ```javascript
   const isChecked = $('#myCheckbox').is(':checked');
   ```

The `checked` property returns a boolean value, so you can use it directly in conditional statements:

```javascript
if (checkbox.checked) {
    console.log('Checkbox is checked');
}
```

This approach is efficient, readable, and widely supported across all modern browsers. It's also worth noting that the `checked` property reflects the current state of the checkbox, so it will update if the user interacts with the checkbox, making it reliable for real-time checking.
