what if we kept the `setKioskMode(kioskToggle.checked);` and just returned 204 from the `toggle_kiosk_mode` view? Then we don't have to swap out any HTML elements and animations would work.
That's an excellent idea! This approach would indeed be more efficient and provide a smoother user experience. Here's how you can implement this:

1. Update your Django view:

```python
from django.http import HttpResponse

def toggle_kiosk_mode(request):
    current_mode = request.COOKIES.get('kiosk_mode', 'off')
    new_mode = 'on' if current_mode == 'off' else 'off'

    response = HttpResponse(status=204)  # 204 No Content
    response.set_cookie('kiosk_mode', new_mode, max_age=30*24*60*60)  # 30 days expiry

    return response
```

2. Update your HTML:

```html
{% from "rainbow/components/tooltip/macros.html" import TooltipItem %}

<div id="kiosk-toggle" class="_flex _items-center _tooltip_wrapper">
    <input type="checkbox"
           class="_toggle-field"
           {% if kiosk_mode == 'on' %}checked{% endif %}
           hx-get="{{ url('interests:toggle-kiosk-mode') }}"
           hx-trigger="change"
           hx-swap="none"
           id="kiosk-mode"
           name="kiosk-mode">
    <label for="kiosk-mode">
        <span class="_sr-only">{{ _('Kiosk Mode') }}</span>
    </label>
    {% call TooltipItem(extra_classes='_bg-lilac-100 _min-w-max _mt-1') %}
    <div class="_normal-case _text-left _text-white _body-xs">{{ _('Kiosk Mode') }}</div>
    {% endcall %}
</div>
```

3. Update your TypeScript file:

```typescript
import onLoad from '../../../static/js/onLoad';
import querySelectorOrThrow from '../../../static/js/querySelectorOrThrow';

const setKioskMode = (isActive: boolean) => {
    document.cookie = `kiosk_mode=${isActive ? 'on' : 'off'}; path=/; max-age=${30*24*60*60}`;
};

const isKioskMode = () => document.cookie.includes('kiosk_mode=on');

const hideKioskElements = () => {
    const active = isKioskMode();
    document.body
        .querySelectorAll('.hide-for-kiosk-mode')
        .forEach((e) => e.classList.toggle('!_hidden', active));
};

const initKioskMode = () => {
    const kioskToggle = querySelectorOrThrow<HTMLInputElement>(
        document,
        '#kiosk-mode'
    );

    kioskToggle.checked = isKioskMode();

    hideKioskElements();

    kioskToggle.addEventListener('change', () => {
        setKioskMode(kioskToggle.checked);
        hideKioskElements();
    });

    document.body.addEventListener('htmx:afterOnLoad', () => {
        hideKioskElements();
    });
};

onLoad(() => {
    initKioskMode();
});
```

This approach offers several benefits:

1. Reduced server load: The server only needs to set a cookie and return a 204 status, without rendering any HTML.
2. Smoother UI: There's no HTML swapping, so any CSS transitions or animations will work seamlessly.
3. Faster response: Since there's no content to transfer, the response will be quicker.
4. Simplified client-side logic: The JavaScript handles the UI updates directly, without waiting for new HTML from the server.

The `setKioskMode` function now updates the cookie directly on the client side, mirroring what the server does. This ensures that the client-side state stays in sync with the server-side state.

Remember to adjust the cookie settings (like path and max-age) to match your server-side settings.

This solution gives you the best of both worlds: server-side persistence with the cookie, and smooth, immediate client-side UI updates.



