 if the element in getCtaName is an input type=checkbox then I want to append the value "on" or "off" to the name as well

Certainly! Let's modify the `getCtaName` function to handle checkboxes specially. Here's the updated version:

```javascript
function getCtaName(element) {
  const overriddenName = element.getAttribute('data-cta-tracker-name');
  const title = element.getAttribute('title');
  const ariaLabel = element.getAttribute('aria-label');
  const fallback = element.innerText;

  let ctaName = overriddenName || title || ariaLabel || fallback;
  ctaName = ctaName.trim();

  // Special handling for checkboxes
  if (element.tagName === 'INPUT' && element.type === 'checkbox') {
    const checkboxState = element.checked ? 'on' : 'off';
    ctaName = `${ctaName} (${checkboxState})`;
  }

  return ctaName;
}
```

This modification does the following:

1. It checks if the element is an input of type checkbox.
2. If it is, it determines the checkbox state (checked or unchecked).
3. It then appends either "(on)" or "(off)" to the CTA name.

With this change, checkbox interactions will be tracked like this:

```html
<input type="checkbox" data-cta-tracker-name="Remember Me" id="remember-me">
<label for="remember-me">Remember Me</label>
```

Output when checked: User clicked the "Remember Me (on)" button
Output when unchecked: User clicked the "Remember Me (off)" button

